{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646715"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.71,0.11,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63151"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"8124"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECorticosteroids are a class of steroid hormones that are commonly used in the treatment of various inflammatory and autoimmune conditions. They have a range of physiological effects on the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following effects is commonly associated with the use of corticosteroids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gain in potassium","Increased blood pressure","Decreased blood glucose levels","Increased bone density","Reduced risk of infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe use of corticosteroids is commonly associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because corticosteroids can cause sodium retention, leading to fluid retention and increased blood volume, which raises blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGain in potassium\u003C/strong\u003E - Corticosteroids can cause hypokalaemia, not a gain in potassium, due to increased renal excretion of potassium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood glucose levels\u003C/strong\u003E - Corticosteroids typically increase blood glucose levels by promoting gluconeogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bone density\u003C/strong\u003E - Long-term use of corticosteroids can lead to decreased bone density and osteoporosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced risk of infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Corticosteroids can suppress the immune system, increasing the risk of infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Corticosteroids can lead to increased blood pressure due to their effect on sodium retention and fluid balance.","Corticosteroids can cause hypokalaemia by promoting renal potassium excretion.","Corticosteroids have anti-inflammatory and immunosuppressive effects, which are utilised in various medical treatments."],"references":["Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527","Carter GT, Duong V, Ho S, Ngo KC, Greer CL, Weeks DL. Side effects of commonly prescribed analgesic medications. Phys Med Rehabil Clin N Am. 2014 May;25(2):457-70. doi: 10.1016/j.pmr.2014.01.007. PMID: 24787343","Rice JB, White AG, Scarpati LM, Wan G, Nelson WW. Long-term Systemic Corticosteroid Exposure: A Systematic Literature Review. Clin Ther. 2017 Nov;39(11):2216-2229. doi: 10.1016/j.clinthera.2017.09.011. Epub 2017 Oct 19. PMID: 29055500."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63151"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63151"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:52:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:06:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10917"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving in